    "raw": "---\ntitle: \"Why chat assistants are not enough for real work\"\ndescription: \"ChatGPT and Claude are great at drafting — but autonomous ops need execution, persistence, and proof. See how Construct compares to chat assistants.\"\ndate: \"2026-06-15\"\nauthor: \"Construct Team\"\ntags: [\"comparison\", \"chatgpt\", \"seo\"]\ndraft: false\n---\n\nChat assistants changed how we draft emails and brainstorm ideas. They are less useful when the job is **do the thing** — across multiple apps, on a schedule, with an audit trail.\n\n## The execution gap\n\nA chat assistant can tell you how to update a spreadsheet, export a PDF, and post to Slack. Construct opens the browser, runs the export, saves the file to your workspace, and posts the summary — then logs every step.\n\nThat gap shows up in three places:\n\n1. **Persistence** — Construct keeps sandbox files and memory across days, not just the current thread.\n2. **Integrations** — 1,000+ connected apps the agent acts on directly, not via copy-paste.\n3. **Proof** — audit log, sent email, and workspace artifacts instead of chat text alone.\n\n## Read the full comparison\n\nWe wrote a detailed breakdown: [Construct vs ChatGPT](/vs/chatgpt).\n\nFor automation builders, see [Construct vs Zapier](/vs/zapier). For suite copilots, see [Construct vs Copilot](/vs/copilot).\n"
